"Viau A.E., Gajewski K., Sawada M.C., Fines P.","Millennial-scale temperature variations in North America during the Holocene",2006,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","111","9", D09102,"","",,,10.1029/2005JD006031,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33745442290&partnerID=40&md5=32dda11db7d7be91d2adbfeea1091379","Laboratory for Paleoclimatology and Climatology, Department of Geography, University of Ottawa, Ottawa, Ont. K1N 6N5, Canada; Department of Mathematics and Statistics, University of Ottawa, Ottawa, Ont., Canada","Viau, A.E., Laboratory for Paleoclimatology and Climatology, Department of Geography, University of Ottawa, Ottawa, Ont. K1N 6N5, Canada; Gajewski, K., Laboratory for Paleoclimatology and Climatology, Department of Geography, University of Ottawa, Ottawa, Ont. K1N 6N5, Canada; Sawada, M.C., Laboratory for Paleoclimatology and Climatology, Department of Geography, University of Ottawa, Ottawa, Ont. K1N 6N5, Canada; Fines, P., Laboratory for Paleoclimatology and Climatology, Department of Geography, University of Ottawa, Ottawa, Ont. K1N 6N5, Canada, Department of Mathematics and Statistics, University of Ottawa, Ottawa, Ont., Canada","A mean continental July temperature reconstruction based on pollen records from across North America quantifies temperature variations of several timescales for the past 14,000 cal yr BP. In North America, temperatures increased nearly 4°C during the late glacial, reaching maximum values between 6000 and 3000 cal yr BP, after which mean July temperatures decreased. Superimposed on this orbital-scale trend are millennial-scale temperature variations that appear coherent in structure and frequency with high-resolution ice, marine and other terrestrial paleoclimate records of the Holocene. During the Holocene, climate in North America appears to have varied periodically every ∼1100 years rather than the ∼1500 year cycle found during the last glacial period. Coherence at frequencies between 900 and 1100 years between land, ice, and ocean records suggests a common forcing associated with widespread surface impacts during the Holocene. These results provide important insight to the global warming debate, as the observed twentieth century temperature increase appears unprecedented compared to our mean North American temperature reconstruction of the past 14,000 years. Copyright 2006 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric temperature; Climate change; Climatology; Glacial geology; climate variation; Holocene; paleoclimate; paleotemperature; North America",,,,,,"Alley, R.B., Mayewski, P.A., Sowers, T., Stuiver, M., Taylor, K.C., Clark, P.U., Holocene climatic instability: A prominent widespread event 8200 yr ago (1997) Geology, 25, pp. 483-486; Anderson, P., Bartlein, P.J., Brubaker, L., Gajewski, K., Ritchie, J., Modern analogues of Late Quaternary pollen spectra from the western interior of North America (1989) J. Biogeogr., 16, pp. 573-596; Avizinis, J., Webb III, T., The computer file of modern pollen and climatic data at Brown University (1985), Dep. of Geol. Sci., Brown Univ., Providence, R. IBerger, A., Loutre, M.F., Insolation values for the climate of the last 10 million years (1991) Quat. Sci. Rev., 10, pp. 297-317; Bianchi, G.G., McCave, I.N., Holocene periodicity in North Atlantic climate and deep-ocean flow south of Iceland (1999) Nature, 397, pp. 515-517; Bond, G., Showers, W., Cheseby, M., Lotti, R., Almasi, P., deMenocal, P., Priore, P., Bonani, G., A pervasive millinnial-scale cycle in North Atlantic Holocene and glacial climates (1997) Science, 278, pp. 1257-1265; Bond, G., Kromer, B., Beer, J., Muscheler, R., Evans, N.E., Showers, W., Hoffman, S., Bonani, G., Persistent solar influence on North Atlantic climate during the Holocene (2001) Science, 294, pp. 2130-2136; Broecker, W.S., Denton, G.H., The role of ocean-atmosphere reorganizations in glacial cycles (1989) Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta, 53, pp. 2465-2501; Broecker, W., van Donk, J.